<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TITLE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Map Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to configure the overall lighting, ambient colour, night mode, lamp behaviour, and renderer lighting settings for a light file.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- OVERVIEW -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Opening Map Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Map Properties</Bold> tab contains the overall lighting settings for the loaded
        light file. These settings affect the whole map and are used alongside individual placed
        light entries.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        To begin editing these values, select the <Bold>Map Properties</Bold> button or tab from
        the main editor display.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/map_properties_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/map_properties_full_panel.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- FLAGS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Lighting Flags
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The first section contains flags that control broad map lighting behaviour. Set these
        according to the type of atmosphere you want the level to have.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/map_properties_flags.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">
        Night Enabled
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Enables night-time lighting for the map. Use this when the level should appear as a night
        scene or a very dark environment.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Note:</Run>
                <Run>
                    In Urban Chaos, enabling night mode also means the map is treated as raining.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">
        Lamps On
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Controls whether street lamps and other light-emitting prims are switched on.
        If this box is checked, lamp prims will emit light. If it is not checked, those lamps
        remain switched off.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">
        Darken Walls
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Slightly darkens the lower portion of facet textures. This can help walls appear less flat
        and can add extra depth to building surfaces.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- AMBIENT LIGHT -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Ambient Light
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The most important overall value to set is <Bold>Ambient</Bold>. Ambient light acts like
        a global colour filter applied across the whole map. It controls the general colour mood
        of the level.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        You can set the Ambient RGB values to any colour you want. For example, setting Ambient to
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">0, 0, 255</Run>
        gives the whole map a strong blue tone. This can be useful for early morning, cold,
        night-time, or low-light scenes.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/map_properties_ambient.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Think of Ambient as the overall colour grade of the level. Individual lights add local colour and brightness,
                    but Ambient defines the general atmosphere of the whole map.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- PREVIEW D3D LIGHTING -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,14,0,2">
        Previewing the Ambient Result
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To preview the effect of the current lighting values, press the
        <Bold>Preview D3D Lighting</Bold> button at the bottom of the Map Properties tab.
        This opens a quick comparison preview showing how the lighting is applied to a base image.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This is useful for quickly judging whether the map feels too bright, too dark, too warm,
        too cold, or too strongly tinted before testing it in the 3D viewport.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/map_properties_preview_d3d_lighting.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- D3D COLOR -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        D3D Color
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>D3D Color</Bold> is a supporting renderer lighting value used by the Direct3D display
        path. Direct3D is the graphics system used by the game to draw the 3D scene, so this value
        can be thought of as an additional renderer-side lighting colour used alongside the main
        Ambient setting.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        In practical terms, Ambient is usually the value you will notice first, while D3D Color
        helps support the way the 3D scene is shaded. If you are unsure what to change, adjust
        Ambient first and leave D3D Color close to its default value.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        D3D Color includes RGB channels and, where shown by the editor, an Alpha channel.
        The RGB values define the colour, while the Alpha value represents the extra channel stored
        with that colour value. A preview swatch appears underneath so you can quickly see the
        selected colour.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/map_properties_d3d_color.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- SPECULAR COLOR -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Specular Color
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Specular Color</Bold> controls the colour used for lighting highlights. These are
        the brighter reflective highlights that can appear on surfaces when light catches them.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Specular Color includes RGB channels and an Alpha channel. The RGB values define the
        highlight colour, while the Alpha value controls the additional stored intensity/alpha
        component for that specular colour. A preview swatch appears underneath the controls.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/map_properties_specular_color.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Specular settings are usually more subtle than Ambient. Use them to tune highlights rather than to set the main mood of the level.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- PRIM LIGHTING -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Prim Lighting
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Prim Lighting</Bold> controls the colour emitted by light-producing prims. The most
        noticeable example is the light coming from street lamp prims.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The default Prim Lighting colour is usually a warm yellow-white:
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">255, 255, 228</Run>.
        This gives street lamps a natural warm glow.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        You can change the RGB values to create different effects, such as colder white lamps,
        blue-tinted lights, red warning lights, or unusual stylised lighting.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,2">
        Prim Light Radius
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Radius</Bold> value controls how many tiles the prim light will cover. Increasing
        the radius makes light-emitting prims affect a wider area of the map.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/map_properties_prim_lighting.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- NIGHT SKY COLOR -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Night Sky Color
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Night Sky Color</Bold> appears to be an unused legacy feature. The game now colours
        the sky using a
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">sky.tga</Run>
        texture file instead.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        It is likely that before textured skies were implemented, the sky used a single default
        colour value. In most modern light files, this setting does not need to be changed.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/map_properties_night_sky_color.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- RECOMMENDED WORKFLOW -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Recommended Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When setting up the overall lighting for a map, a simple workflow is:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Open the <Bold>Map Properties</Bold> tab.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Set the required flags, such as <Bold>Night Enabled</Bold>, <Bold>Lamps On</Bold>, and <Bold>Darken Walls</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Set the <Bold>Ambient</Bold> RGB value to define the overall colour mood.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Use <Bold>Preview D3D Lighting</Bold> to check the result against the preview image.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Adjust <Bold>D3D Color</Bold>, <Bold>Specular Color</Bold>, and <Bold>Prim Lighting</Bold> only as needed.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Test the result in the map view or 3D viewport.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- IMPORTANT NOTE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,10,0,0">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">⚠ Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Ambient lighting can strongly change the appearance of the whole map. Save a copy of the light file before making major changes to the global lighting values.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- NEXT STEPS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Next Steps
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        After configuring the overall map lighting, continue to the
        <Bold>Using the 3D Preview</Bold> section to preview how the lighting looks in a
        three-dimensional view of the map.
    </Paragraph>

</FlowDocument>
